Use conditional compilation or the `MAUI` platform-specific folder convention. The cleanest approach:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under the corresponding `Platforms/` folder (e.g., `Platforms/Android/AndroidNotificationService.cs`), which is already target-compiled per platform by the SDK.

**Alternative** — avoid `#if` directives by placing a partial registration class in each platform folder:

```csharp
// Services/ServiceRegistration.cs (shared)
public static partial class ServiceRegistration
{
    public static partial IServiceCollection AddNotifications(this IServiceCollection services);
}

// Platforms/Android/ServiceRegistration.cs
public static partial class ServiceRegistration
{
    public static partial IServiceCollection AddNotifications(this IServiceCollection services)
        => services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, AndroidNotificationService>();
}
```

Then in `MauiProgram.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddNotifications();
```

Both approaches are safe — the compiler only includes code for the active target platform, so it won't break on any platform.
